A simple mistake as a mere spin will alter the leadership board, these days measured in seconds as witnessed in Monza, Italy, last weekend where world champion Sébastien Ogier beat last year’s champion Ott Tanak by only 13.9 seconds.
A puncture in the Safari will be enough to drop one from pole to being completely out of contention. The general populace and an expected global television of over 70 million  people will follow the action captured on dedicated WRC+ TV channel and in linear television in over 150 countries at the shakedown as a dramatic re-introduction paragraph of the Kenya of the third decade of the 21st century.
Whereas no points are awarded in shakedown stages, it offers a sneak preview of what contenders should expect in the rally proper. Opponents weigh each other and testing the machines remain paramount.
We should congratulate Clerk-of-Course  Gurvir Bhabra and his team of Nazir Yakub — he of the minute-to-detail reputation — 2006 Africa Rally Championship (ARC) Safari Rally winning navigator George Mwangi and legendary photojournalist Anwar Sidi for a job well done.
They are not yet done with Loldia until they create a WRC Rally Finland-type concept which will see cars travel at more than 180kph crest over two jumps, taking the fastest airborne  to between 60  and 80 metres.



